  "text": "IL-1β secretion is not a simple consequence of TiO 2 -induced cell death Non-biological particles in a size range that enables phagocytosis, which includes pigment-grade TiO 2 , are readily engulfed by macrophages and accumulate in lysosomes [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This in turn leads to lysosomal membrane disruption which is a trigger for two concomitant events. The first is cathepsin-dependent IL-1β release which requires inflammasome activation, and the second is cell death which again is cathepsin-dependent but is independent of the inflammasome [CITATION_4] . Hence, as expected, both events were observed in this study in a dose-dependent fashion when cells were exposed to TiO 2 . In vivo, cell death can lead to pro-IL-1β leakage into the extracellular environment and its activation through 'alternative' pathways, such as cathepsin Cneutrophil proteases. However, this does not occur in 'clean' cell culture media in vitro [CITATION_5] . Moreover, a short 'pulse and chase' routine protects against such longer term complications. It is therefore anticipated that our observed IL-1β-inducing effect of TiO 2 in LPS-primed macrophages is independent of the concomitantly observed cell death. Regardless of mechanism, it does not alter the potential relevance of these findings to the in vivo situation where, as noted, pigment-grade TiO 2 accumulates in selective intestinal cells of humans.",
